WEBVTT

00:05.090 --> 00:07.010
DOUGLAS: Previously on Billions...

00:07.090 --> 00:08.970
Taylor wants to destroy us.

00:09.050 --> 00:11.260
They took the firefighters
not because

00:11.340 --> 00:12.720
they needed that
particular money

00:12.800 --> 00:14.180
but as a straight-up
"fuck you" to me.

00:14.260 --> 00:16.340
What would Axe say
if he knew about this?

00:16.430 --> 00:18.760
This has nothing to do with him.

00:18.840 --> 00:21.130
Commissioner Sansome,
I wonder if I could trouble you

00:21.220 --> 00:22.890
on the small matter
of a carry permit

00:22.970 --> 00:24.550
for a client of mine.

00:24.640 --> 00:26.550
I'd like your permission
to see someone professional.

00:26.640 --> 00:28.260
A dom?

00:28.340 --> 00:30.340
You know I'm committed
to my government post...

00:30.430 --> 00:32.090
The Secretary of the Treasury.

00:32.180 --> 00:35.800
But, I do like to keep an eye
peeled for opportunities.

00:35.890 --> 00:37.760
We need a strategic partnership.

00:37.840 --> 00:39.930
Brian Dana's the right partner
for this project.

00:40.010 --> 00:41.680
Taylor needs to be
the one to crush it.

00:41.760 --> 00:43.590
WENDY: That will be
the most devastating blow.

00:43.680 --> 00:45.090
With their dad in town,

00:45.180 --> 00:45.890
they're working on
something together.

00:45.970 --> 00:46.840
Sounds sweet.

00:46.930 --> 00:48.510
Right. Yeah.

00:48.590 --> 00:50.300
Could be big too.

00:50.390 --> 00:52.510
Applying for a wiretap.
On Charles Rhoades, Senior.

00:52.590 --> 00:53.970
CONNERTY: Junior, too, actually.

00:54.050 --> 00:55.510
FBI observed father and son

00:55.590 --> 00:57.260
on the building site
in question.

01:04.720 --> 01:09.390
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

01:09.470 --> 01:14.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:14.470 --> 01:19.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:19.220 --> 01:21.180
You said 'emergency.'

01:21.260 --> 01:23.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:23.680 --> 01:25.390
[SIGHS]

01:25.470 --> 01:28.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:28.970 --> 01:32.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:32.590 --> 01:34.430
Look out there.

01:34.510 --> 01:38.180
BROGAN: It's a Belgian Malinois.

01:38.260 --> 01:40.970
Is that your dog?

01:41.050 --> 01:42.510
Neighbor's.

01:42.590 --> 01:43.590
Is it...?

01:43.680 --> 01:45.180
Dead? Yes.

01:45.260 --> 01:48.220
Are you drunk?

01:48.300 --> 01:49.640
No.

01:49.720 --> 01:51.090
I've been drinking.
It's different.

01:51.180 --> 01:53.970
What the fuck did you do?

01:54.050 --> 01:57.430
The wife and I had a fight.

01:57.510 --> 02:02.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:02.300 --> 02:04.050
She decamped to the Baccarat.

02:04.130 --> 02:05.430
That storm earlier?

02:05.510 --> 02:08.180
Rain was coming down.
It was dark as hell.

02:08.259 --> 02:10.009
I hear this banging
at the back door,

02:10.090 --> 02:12.130
saw a figure and fired.

02:12.220 --> 02:14.390
It was instinct.
I'm a man of action.

02:14.470 --> 02:16.050
Mm-hmm.

02:16.130 --> 02:17.890
Why did you call me?

02:17.970 --> 02:20.180
You're my Michael Clayton.

02:20.260 --> 02:24.470
I'm the Attorney General
of the State of... No.

02:24.550 --> 02:26.010
Cops come yet?

02:26.090 --> 02:28.890
I'm hoping anyone around
who heard the shot,

02:28.970 --> 02:30.180
they thought it was thunder...

02:30.260 --> 02:32.640
[KNOCK ON DOOR]
Who's that?

02:32.720 --> 02:35.180
The cops.
You know, "They don't call."

02:35.260 --> 02:36.840
Uh, I can buy us some time,

02:36.930 --> 02:38.590
but we're in a big
fucking jackpot here.

02:38.680 --> 02:40.840
You'd better engage a lawyer.

02:40.930 --> 02:43.090
Try this one.

02:43.180 --> 02:45.390
Now I'm gonna go out there
and try to make it

02:45.470 --> 02:47.590
that you don't
get arrested tonight.

02:47.680 --> 02:51.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:51.510 --> 02:55.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:55.130 --> 02:58.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:58.720 --> 03:00.550
Oh, hello, officers.

03:00.640 --> 03:02.890
Perhaps you recognize me.

03:02.970 --> 03:06.930
[URINATING]

03:07.010 --> 03:10.510
Mr. Secretary.

03:10.590 --> 03:12.090
Mr. Attorney General.

03:12.180 --> 03:14.680
Ah, you can call me Jock.

03:14.760 --> 03:16.680
Jock.
[URINATING]

03:16.760 --> 03:18.550
I always assumed
you got your nickname

03:18.640 --> 03:19.800
because you were an athlete.

03:19.890 --> 03:21.720
Yeah, not exactly.

03:21.800 --> 03:24.220
I see that.

03:27.720 --> 03:30.090
Those little flies
painted in the basin,

03:30.180 --> 03:32.130
they're good targets,
aren't they?

03:32.220 --> 03:33.680
Indeed.

03:33.760 --> 03:35.510
Yeah, men need targets.

03:35.590 --> 03:37.130
Keep things neat.

03:37.220 --> 03:41.220
Sometimes men become targets.

03:41.300 --> 03:44.930
No one likes to get pissed on.

03:45.010 --> 03:48.760
You should know that
you are a target.

03:48.840 --> 03:52.510
Chuck Rhoades has you
in his sights.

03:52.590 --> 03:55.680
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:55.760 --> 03:58.760
[ZIPS]

03:58.840 --> 04:02.390
I'd appreciate any details
you could provide.

04:02.470 --> 04:06.590
Well, I have been singing
the tune of the tufted titmouse,

04:06.680 --> 04:08.970
but now I gotta go silent.

04:09.050 --> 04:11.340
[URINAL FLUSHES]

04:11.430 --> 04:14.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:14.470 --> 04:17.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:17.550 --> 04:20.930
[DOORBELL RINGS]

04:22.430 --> 04:26.260
You want some
Uova Picante Purgatorio?

04:26.340 --> 04:28.720
That's Eggs in... Purgatory, yes.

04:28.800 --> 04:30.260
But no.

04:30.340 --> 04:32.590
Close enough to that place
as it is, Commissioner.

04:32.680 --> 04:34.550
That's why I'm here.
[CHUCKLES]

04:34.640 --> 04:36.970
Sure is.

04:37.050 --> 04:40.470
Come on.

04:43.430 --> 04:44.930
Oh.

04:45.010 --> 04:46.340
There it is, huh?

04:46.430 --> 04:48.300
The Little League trophy!

04:48.390 --> 04:49.930
To the victor.

04:50.010 --> 04:52.390
You know, I'm glad I was able to
help you with that.

04:52.470 --> 04:53.890
That thing's in the rearview.

04:53.970 --> 04:55.430
I'm already onto next year.

04:55.510 --> 04:57.760
Ah.

04:57.840 --> 05:00.220
Right to it, then.

05:00.300 --> 05:02.390
This is why you don't
put a weapon

05:02.470 --> 05:04.050
in the hands of an amateur.

05:04.130 --> 05:06.220
I suppose we both bear
some blame for that.

05:06.300 --> 05:07.550
Unh-unh-unh.
I bear nothing.

05:07.640 --> 05:09.180
And you're gonna
make sure of that.

05:09.260 --> 05:10.890
Yes.
And to that end,

05:10.970 --> 05:14.050
the neighbor might not yet know
his dog is dead.

05:14.130 --> 05:15.800
Even when he finds out,

05:15.890 --> 05:19.430
he won't find this.

05:19.510 --> 05:21.050
You brought that
fucking thing here?

05:21.130 --> 05:22.590
So we can make it go away.

05:22.680 --> 05:24.550
Hey, stop with the "we" shit.

05:24.640 --> 05:26.640
Neither of us should be
in the middle of this.

05:26.720 --> 05:29.180
[CHUCKLES] Well,
Brogan says I'm his fixer.

05:29.260 --> 05:31.340
What, like Michael Clayton?

05:31.430 --> 05:33.260
We did get him the carry permit,

05:33.340 --> 05:35.300
so it's reasonable
that he believes...

05:35.390 --> 05:38.010
We again! Stop that or
I'll brain ya with the trophy.

05:38.090 --> 05:41.010
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

05:41.090 --> 05:43.430
What the real Michael Clayton
would know is,

05:43.510 --> 05:45.390
we are the exact people
who can't.

05:45.470 --> 05:47.930
I can't. My signature's
on the permit.

05:48.010 --> 05:49.930
It'll look like
I'm helping myself.

05:50.010 --> 05:51.220
No, counselor.

05:51.300 --> 05:52.680
You, alone,
have to make this right.

05:52.760 --> 05:54.260
For all of us.

05:54.340 --> 05:56.180
Because if it comes out that
you influence peddled

05:56.260 --> 05:58.130
a gun permit that killed a dog,

05:58.220 --> 06:00.590
our reps and our careers
are gonna be deader

06:00.680 --> 06:02.010
than that poor mutt.

06:02.090 --> 06:03.720
It was a pure-breed.

06:03.800 --> 06:05.180
Just like you.

06:05.260 --> 06:07.510
So go fix it.

06:07.590 --> 06:09.260
Now.

06:09.340 --> 06:10.840
Leave me to my damn
eggs and gravy.

06:10.930 --> 06:15.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:15.970 --> 06:17.930
Let's call this
off-site to order.

06:18.010 --> 06:19.800
That's a little extreme,
isn't it,

06:19.890 --> 06:21.640
meeting here in
your secret clubhouse?

06:21.720 --> 06:23.430
Well, no one needs to see this...

06:23.510 --> 06:25.300
Or you coming in
and out of Axe Cap

06:25.390 --> 06:27.220
while we're about to
give you this task,

06:27.300 --> 06:29.720
should you choose to accept it.

06:29.800 --> 06:31.130
Besides...

06:31.220 --> 06:32.510
This idea's a winner for you.

06:32.590 --> 06:34.260
Aerospace innovation.

06:34.340 --> 06:36.890
Plenty of upside, or I wouldn't
have brought it to you.

06:36.970 --> 06:39.510
Brian Dana, 375Y.
He's the VC partner.

06:39.590 --> 06:42.050
Smart guy, good shop,
for his scale.

06:42.130 --> 06:44.090
I'm not gonna lie to you.

06:44.180 --> 06:47.800
The developer behind this tech
is Douglas Mason.

06:47.890 --> 06:50.090
Taylor's father.

06:51.220 --> 06:53.090
Big fucking drop.

06:53.180 --> 06:55.180
But it's a solid play.
It's been vetted.

06:55.260 --> 06:56.930
Vetted for making money

06:57.010 --> 06:59.470
or for making Taylor's head
explode like in Scanners?

06:59.550 --> 07:01.930
Bit of both.

07:02.010 --> 07:04.260
Glad to know up front this time.

07:04.340 --> 07:06.300
And know this up front,

07:06.390 --> 07:08.640
I'll lock in a price
so that I can buy it from you

07:08.720 --> 07:11.180
once you control it,
at a healthy profit.

07:11.260 --> 07:12.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:13.010 --> 07:15.890
AXE: So get in there.

07:15.970 --> 07:17.470
AXE: Make 'em an offer
they can't refuse.

07:17.550 --> 07:19.090
WENDY: Go in on
an entire slate,

07:19.180 --> 07:20.340
so you can disguise the intent.

07:20.430 --> 07:22.510
REBECCA: Oh, I will.

07:22.590 --> 07:24.550
REBECCA: That's what I do.

07:24.640 --> 07:26.510
We have already won.

07:26.590 --> 07:27.800
We've doubled up.

07:27.890 --> 07:30.340
Big VC player... Rebecca Cantu...

07:30.430 --> 07:31.890
Wants to put in
a hundred million

07:31.970 --> 07:33.890
and ramp up the timetable
to production.

07:33.970 --> 07:35.760
That's what I'm talking about!

07:35.840 --> 07:37.970
People seeing
the intrinsic value.

07:38.050 --> 07:39.510
What kind of controls
will we have?

07:39.590 --> 07:41.390
What kind of say when
it comes to development,

07:41.470 --> 07:43.260
deployment, personnel
on a go-forward?

07:43.340 --> 07:44.970
All to be negotiated.

07:45.050 --> 07:46.840
But my father, he'd still be
driving the R&D,

07:46.930 --> 07:48.130
the production...

07:48.220 --> 07:50.010
Exactly what I was going to ask.

07:50.090 --> 07:53.590
This Rebecca Cantu is clearly
a very smart woman.

07:53.680 --> 07:55.800
She's buying your idea,
she's buying you, right?

07:55.890 --> 07:57.720
It's a good point.

07:57.800 --> 08:00.010
So you'll sit with her
as soon as we close.

08:00.090 --> 08:01.800
I imagine the moment
she sits with you,

08:01.890 --> 08:04.130
she'll realize
how crucial you are.

08:04.220 --> 08:06.890
"Imagine me and you.
I do.

08:06.970 --> 08:08.340
Happy together."

08:08.430 --> 08:09.800
Most folks think
that's a love song,

08:09.890 --> 08:11.680
but if you listen closely,
you'll hear it's about

08:11.760 --> 08:15.390
a relationship that never
actually happened.

08:15.470 --> 08:18.510
The key to unlocking it
is that word, "imagine."

08:20.260 --> 08:23.090
Taylor and I are going to
step out for a microsecond.

08:28.590 --> 08:30.180
[DOOR OPENS]

08:33.220 --> 08:34.679
I see where
you're going with this.

08:34.760 --> 08:36.390
And now is the pause

08:36.470 --> 08:38.010
where we think this through
before you do.

08:38.090 --> 08:41.090
Because we would clear
38% on our investment...

08:41.179 --> 08:43.429
In a matter of months.

08:43.510 --> 08:46.680
And your father walks
with over five million...

08:46.760 --> 08:48.930
The walking part is the problem.

08:49.010 --> 08:51.720
They will broom him... if not
right away, then soon enough.

08:51.800 --> 08:54.090
Returns like this could
tell the story of our firm

08:54.180 --> 08:56.220
for the next five years.

08:56.300 --> 08:57.680
You're right.

08:57.760 --> 08:59.050
And you were right
to pull me out here,

08:59.130 --> 09:00.640
so I could have
a moment to think,

09:00.720 --> 09:02.640
hear what I need in order to
frame the decision.

09:04.000 --> 09:10.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

09:19.390 --> 09:20.930
This is exciting, but...

09:21.010 --> 09:23.130
Taylor Mason Capital passed.

09:23.220 --> 09:27.090
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

09:27.180 --> 09:28.840
Really?

09:28.930 --> 09:30.720
You pass?
How can you pass?

09:30.800 --> 09:32.640
Keeping my father in place
is my highest priority

09:32.720 --> 09:34.470
and the key to our success.

09:34.550 --> 09:36.640
If we can't guarantee that,
then there is no deal.

09:36.720 --> 09:37.800
And if this is just
the early action,

09:37.890 --> 09:39.090
I'd rather let
the interest grow...

09:39.180 --> 09:40.680
We'll do even better later.

09:40.760 --> 09:42.300
Okay, Taylor.
If that's what you want to do,

09:42.390 --> 09:45.180
that's what we'll do.

09:45.260 --> 09:47.050
[CLEARS THROAT]

09:47.130 --> 09:48.890
HAMMON: I'll walk you out.

09:48.970 --> 09:50.010
Thank you.

09:50.090 --> 09:51.840
Taylor chose their father

09:51.930 --> 09:54.010
over the short term hit
for their business.

09:54.090 --> 09:56.090
Great stressors
can be bonding agents

09:56.180 --> 09:58.090
instead of tearing them apart.

09:58.180 --> 10:01.220
And Taylor will feel quite good
about themself right now.

10:01.300 --> 10:03.090
Fuck.

10:03.180 --> 10:05.090
But the other pressure...

10:05.180 --> 10:08.470
Living up to this perfect vision
of who they're trying to be...

10:08.550 --> 10:11.840
Everything to their father...
That will build.

10:11.930 --> 10:13.340
How fast?

10:13.430 --> 10:15.050
Depends.
Can you accelerate it?

10:15.130 --> 10:16.800
How far do you need me
to push this?

10:16.890 --> 10:19.180
All the fucking way.
You really wanted this,

10:19.260 --> 10:21.130
and I'm sorry that I couldn't
make it happen for you.

10:21.220 --> 10:23.970
No.
No, it was a useful attempt.

10:24.050 --> 10:26.470
Just showed me there may not be
a standard business solution

10:26.550 --> 10:28.680
to get Taylor to
betray their father.

10:28.760 --> 10:31.050
Well, then I guess we're done
looking for standard solutions.

10:31.130 --> 10:33.180
Goody gumdrops.

10:33.260 --> 10:35.050
I'll be at the office.

10:35.130 --> 10:36.890
Thinking.
Planning.

10:36.970 --> 10:39.970
Sure, say it, scheming.

10:49.010 --> 10:50.430
All righty.

10:50.510 --> 10:52.510
Uh, get you gentlemen anything?

10:52.590 --> 10:54.390
How are your whiskey stores?

10:54.470 --> 10:56.220
Shut for winter.

10:56.300 --> 10:59.390
Well, hold onto your shtreimels,
because I got this done.

10:59.470 --> 11:02.890
Purchased your neighbor's
silence for 100K.

11:02.970 --> 11:04.970
Okay.

11:05.050 --> 11:08.550
Oh, and a new Malinois puppy,

11:08.640 --> 11:10.550
of show quality.

11:10.640 --> 11:12.720
Fuck.

11:12.800 --> 11:15.050
That's gonna cost me
thousands more.

11:15.130 --> 11:17.300
Especially if I have to jump up
the line at a top breeder.

11:17.390 --> 11:20.010
CHUCK: Mm.
[CHUCKLES]

11:20.090 --> 11:22.050
Mm.

11:22.130 --> 11:25.930
Feature me in a beret
and I'll paint you a picture.

11:26.010 --> 11:29.050
You'll do time for
illegal discharge of a weapon.

11:29.130 --> 11:31.970
My public service career
will be burnt toast.

11:32.050 --> 11:36.970
And you'll be known the world
over as a drunken dog-killer.

11:37.050 --> 11:41.050
Well, when you put it that way,
I accept the deal.

11:41.130 --> 11:44.760
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

11:44.840 --> 11:46.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:46.680 --> 11:48.720
Ready to hit it?
Yeah.

11:48.800 --> 11:51.180
Hey, Bobby, heard you were
talking about

11:51.260 --> 11:52.430
buying something before,

11:52.510 --> 11:53.680
and I've been waiting
to tell you

11:53.760 --> 11:55.260
about something like that too.

11:55.340 --> 11:57.430
Now seems like the best time.

11:57.510 --> 11:59.550
I got an offer
to sell this place.

11:59.640 --> 12:01.550
Had my eye on
a property in Florida.

12:01.640 --> 12:03.680
I can roll the money
right into it.

12:03.760 --> 12:07.430
They offered me
close to a million dollars.

12:07.510 --> 12:09.680
[LAUGHS]
You imagine that?

12:09.760 --> 12:11.680
An old paesan like me.

12:11.760 --> 12:13.640
Okay.
So we'll open in Florida?

12:13.720 --> 12:16.050
No, kid, can't.
You can't.

12:16.130 --> 12:18.840
The water's not the same so
the crust wouldn't be either.

12:18.930 --> 12:20.050
Well, I'll fly in
the New York water.

12:20.130 --> 12:21.680
People do it.

12:21.760 --> 12:23.970
Nah.

12:24.050 --> 12:26.220
You know, beach time for me.

12:26.300 --> 12:28.680
Calm, calm.

12:28.760 --> 12:31.050
Let's do this.
I'll advance you the money

12:31.130 --> 12:32.470
so you can get
that property that you want.

12:32.550 --> 12:34.180
Against a purchase price.

12:34.260 --> 12:36.890
Meanwhile, you train
a replacement for here,

12:36.970 --> 12:39.220
spend a couple of months
in the winter down there.

12:39.300 --> 12:40.970
Come back refreshed.

12:41.050 --> 12:44.390
And we plan for, what,
five years from now,

12:44.470 --> 12:45.890
transition is complete,

12:45.970 --> 12:47.890
and you're living down there
full time.

12:50.180 --> 12:51.840
Yeah, yeah.

12:51.930 --> 12:53.640
Sure, Bobby, if you think
that's the way that's best.

12:53.720 --> 12:55.090
Yeah, good.

12:55.180 --> 12:56.890
Okay, good. It's settled.
Good.

12:56.970 --> 12:58.430
And we'll work out a number.

12:58.510 --> 13:00.470
Whatever you think.

13:03.220 --> 13:04.640
You should head back to the city
ahead of me.

13:04.720 --> 13:06.260
I'll catch up later.

13:06.340 --> 13:07.890
All right.
Bye.

13:10.010 --> 13:11.640
I need to use the back office
for the next few hours.

13:11.720 --> 13:13.010
Go right in there.
Help yourself.

13:13.090 --> 13:14.720
All right.
Sure.

13:18.130 --> 13:19.300
So, are you downsizing?

13:19.390 --> 13:22.840
Uh, no.
It's...

13:22.930 --> 13:25.760
Right now, a change
feels necessary.

13:25.840 --> 13:28.010
I understand.
We'll find just the buyer.

13:28.090 --> 13:29.890
BRIENNE: I'll let you know
what price I recommend.

13:29.970 --> 13:31.970
This place will be
a hit on Zillow.

13:32.050 --> 13:33.720
You're going to do very well
when we sell.

13:33.800 --> 13:34.930
WENDY: Great.

13:38.510 --> 13:39.430
[SCOFFS]

13:39.510 --> 13:41.970
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

13:42.050 --> 13:45.720
We haven't listed it yet.

13:45.800 --> 13:47.550
I should hope not.

13:47.640 --> 13:50.470
But I did ask her to come over
and put a value on it,

13:50.550 --> 13:52.180
a price at which
she thinks it'll move.

13:52.260 --> 13:55.840
I don't remember us
talking about this.

13:55.930 --> 13:58.130
Oh, I know why.
Because we didn't.

14:00.340 --> 14:01.680
I don't want to
blow up our family.

14:01.760 --> 14:03.130
Or accept that you did.

14:03.220 --> 14:05.680
But I don't see us
staying intact here

14:05.760 --> 14:07.760
after everything
that's happened.

14:07.840 --> 14:10.430
I mean, you sent us
out of this very house,

14:10.510 --> 14:12.840
that another woman
could come in and...

14:12.930 --> 14:15.970
Using our house was your idea.

14:16.050 --> 14:17.720
You didn't have to
say yes to it.

14:19.640 --> 14:22.760
But that's not nearly all.

14:22.840 --> 14:24.930
This place doesn't feel

14:25.010 --> 14:28.050
very much like a home to me
right now.

14:30.840 --> 14:33.050
I know that feeling.

14:35.800 --> 14:38.680
It's how I felt,
often, growing up.

14:42.260 --> 14:46.220
I promised myself I'd never
create an environment where...

14:51.010 --> 14:54.180
Have I ever told you
the pancake eater story?

14:54.260 --> 14:56.970
No, I'd remember the name of
something like that.

14:57.050 --> 14:59.430
Yes, you would.
[CHUCKLES]

15:02.470 --> 15:05.840
Sundays as a kid,

15:05.930 --> 15:07.220
it was when we were
the closest thing

15:07.300 --> 15:10.130
to what most folks would
consider a family.

15:10.220 --> 15:13.510
I'd wake up to the smell
of pancakes and bacon

15:13.590 --> 15:16.970
inundating the apartment.

15:17.050 --> 15:21.430
My mother always gave the girl
the day off on Sundays.

15:21.510 --> 15:23.130
That's how she'd put it anyway.

15:23.220 --> 15:24.930
And took great pride
in preparing

15:25.010 --> 15:27.390
this incredible spread.

15:27.470 --> 15:29.800
Orange juice,
fresh squeezed in a carafe.

15:29.890 --> 15:32.300
The effect was stunning.

15:32.390 --> 15:35.390
And as my mother put out these
perfectly prepared pancakes...

15:35.470 --> 15:38.130
Pat of butter on top,
syrup running down the sides

15:38.220 --> 15:39.970
right on the plate,

15:40.050 --> 15:42.130
Dad would sit down
with the paper,

15:42.220 --> 15:44.130
at the head of the table,
and he'd tell her,

15:44.220 --> 15:47.470
and me, that... oh, ho... this...

15:47.550 --> 15:50.970
This was living.

15:51.050 --> 15:54.090
Oh, Chuck, it's spooky
when you do that.

15:54.180 --> 15:56.260
You sound just like him.

15:56.340 --> 15:58.300
Look like him, too...
Maybe don't do it again.

15:58.390 --> 16:00.970
Spooky part's coming.

16:01.050 --> 16:03.930
Usually, he'd congratulate her
on the effort.

16:04.010 --> 16:05.970
Thank her.

16:06.050 --> 16:08.050
Let her know that, uh,

16:08.130 --> 16:12.050
this was his ideal way
to spend a Sunday.

16:12.130 --> 16:14.010
And as you might infer,

16:14.090 --> 16:16.220
this brought me great lightness.

16:16.300 --> 16:18.640
A respite from the norm.

16:18.720 --> 16:23.050
But then, uh, maybe once a year,
perhaps twice,

16:23.130 --> 16:25.510
upon landing at his seat,
but before sitting,

16:25.590 --> 16:28.680
a scowl would
come across his face.

16:28.760 --> 16:32.010
And my father would

16:32.090 --> 16:35.720
sweep the bacon, carafe of juice

16:35.800 --> 16:38.680
and, yes, those perfect
pancakes, off the table

16:38.760 --> 16:41.840
and onto the floor
in a fit of rage.

16:41.930 --> 16:45.260
And he'd look at
my cowering mother and scream,

16:45.340 --> 16:49.680
"What the hell do I look like,
a goddamned pancake eater?"

16:49.760 --> 16:52.090
And then he'd storm out.

16:52.180 --> 16:56.130
And my mother
would fall to pieces

16:56.220 --> 17:00.130
even as she scrambled to
clean it all up and put it away.

17:00.220 --> 17:02.550
She'd spend the rest of the day

17:02.640 --> 17:05.089
fretting over what she'd done
to set him off,

17:05.180 --> 17:08.930
and hoping he'd come home.

17:09.010 --> 17:12.640
And eventually, he would.

17:12.720 --> 17:16.550
And she'd apologize to him.

17:16.640 --> 17:18.300
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

17:18.390 --> 17:19.970
Good lord.

17:20.050 --> 17:21.839
Yeah, that's not the punchline.

17:21.930 --> 17:23.550
No, the punchline is the night

17:23.640 --> 17:25.470
when I was about
eight-years-old,

17:25.550 --> 17:27.260
and he came into my room,

17:27.339 --> 17:29.930
after one of these
fractious mornings.

17:30.010 --> 17:33.050
"You know why I did what I did,
Sonny?

17:33.130 --> 17:37.130
Keep things fresh
and exciting for her.

17:37.220 --> 17:39.970
So she doesn't take it all
for granted.

17:40.050 --> 17:41.550
And to make her appreciate

17:41.640 --> 17:44.010
the Sundays I don't
break it all apart.

17:44.090 --> 17:46.430
A woman has a subconscious
desire to be dominated.

17:46.510 --> 17:48.430
Remember that.

17:48.510 --> 17:50.390
Use it."

17:50.470 --> 17:53.510
I...

17:53.590 --> 17:56.720
That's where I come from, Wend.

17:56.800 --> 18:01.220
I don't get violent,
throw things or cheat.

18:01.300 --> 18:04.550
But I can't seem to
be normal either.

18:04.640 --> 18:07.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:07.430 --> 18:09.590
I'm trying though.

18:09.680 --> 18:12.720
As hard as I know how.

18:12.800 --> 18:16.010
And I implore you,

18:16.090 --> 18:18.840
don't put our home up for sale.

18:18.930 --> 18:20.760
But rather work with me,

18:20.840 --> 18:23.510
love me as I do you,

18:23.590 --> 18:28.340
and, uh, let's find
our way back.

18:28.430 --> 18:31.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.300 --> 18:34.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:34.220 --> 18:36.220
I'm touched by you
going this deep.

18:36.300 --> 18:38.010
This excavation.

18:38.090 --> 18:42.720
I understand what it takes
to go there and pull it out.

18:42.800 --> 18:45.970
And I want that all
to be enough...

18:46.050 --> 18:48.970
And maybe it would've been
if you told me

18:49.050 --> 18:51.340
before your own pancake eater
moment on TV,

18:51.430 --> 18:52.550
in front of the whole world.

18:52.640 --> 18:55.340
Yeah, I know, I know.

18:55.430 --> 18:56.470
But can you just...

18:56.550 --> 18:58.300
I'm trying to.

18:58.390 --> 19:00.970
The best I know how.

19:01.050 --> 19:03.550
But I can't promise you
anything, Chuck.

19:03.640 --> 19:07.680
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:07.760 --> 19:10.590
[SIGHS]

19:10.680 --> 19:13.720
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:13.800 --> 19:15.640
Your mother's gonna
love this place.

19:15.720 --> 19:17.930
She'll think it too expensive.

19:18.010 --> 19:19.800
Do you?

19:19.890 --> 19:21.300
I wouldn't have offered it
to you if I did.

19:21.390 --> 19:23.970
Besides, the company
will pay for it.

19:24.050 --> 19:27.050
As it should.

19:27.130 --> 19:29.390
It's exactly what I needed.

19:29.470 --> 19:32.180
Enough room to pace.

19:32.260 --> 19:35.470
Enough buildings and sky to
induce productive ideation.

19:35.550 --> 19:38.220
And it will convince Mom,
as well, I hope.

19:38.300 --> 19:40.970
I can't wait for her to be here,
too, actually.

19:41.050 --> 19:43.130
Feelings she also holds.

19:43.220 --> 19:44.590
I can't tell you
the number of times

19:44.680 --> 19:46.300
she wanted us to come visit.

19:46.390 --> 19:49.510
I just wasn't...

19:51.720 --> 19:53.430
It's good you're ready now.

19:53.510 --> 19:56.300
Yeah.
It is.

19:58.340 --> 20:01.550
Reunited and it feels so good.

20:01.640 --> 20:04.590
Dad, did you just quote
a pop song?

20:04.680 --> 20:07.010
[CHUCKLES]

20:07.090 --> 20:08.430
I guess it's catching.

20:08.510 --> 20:12.680
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:12.760 --> 20:17.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:17.180 --> 20:19.890
I come bearing my war club,
to join with yours.

20:19.970 --> 20:21.510
Who are we bludgeoning?

20:21.590 --> 20:24.680
I'm here to tell you
that our interests

20:24.760 --> 20:26.590
are finally 100 percent aligned.

20:26.680 --> 20:28.590
Yeah. I got that part.
Who?

20:28.680 --> 20:32.720
Chuck Rhoades knows about
my Cayman Islands activity.

20:32.800 --> 20:34.340
We can take him out together.

20:34.430 --> 20:36.340
It's what you've always wanted.

20:36.430 --> 20:39.970
Ah, so that dogged prosecutor
has picked up your scent.

20:40.050 --> 20:42.180
Not fun, is it?
No.

20:42.260 --> 20:43.930
Got that river of sweat
running down your crack

20:44.010 --> 20:45.840
like a bombing comedian?

20:45.930 --> 20:47.720
Yes. Mm.

20:47.800 --> 20:48.840
Will you help me?

20:48.930 --> 20:50.300
Of course, Todd.

20:50.390 --> 20:52.180
You merely had to ask.

20:52.260 --> 20:53.890
Shall we prick our thumbs
and bleed them together

20:53.970 --> 20:55.300
like Tom and Huck?

20:55.390 --> 20:57.260
You know, to become
blood brothers?

20:57.340 --> 20:59.640
I feel we already have.

20:59.720 --> 21:01.550
[CHUCKLES]

21:01.640 --> 21:03.510
Jesus, that pizza smells sweet.

21:03.590 --> 21:05.590
Can I get a slice to go?

21:05.680 --> 21:07.470
I'll trade ya a whole pie,

21:07.550 --> 21:09.470
plus solve
your Rhoades problems,

21:09.550 --> 21:12.840
for an introduction to a certain
guy who works for your outfit.

21:12.930 --> 21:14.720
Yeah, anybody.
Who?

21:14.800 --> 21:16.300
Robert Beaufort.

21:16.390 --> 21:18.800
"Hard Bob" Beaufort, huh?

21:18.890 --> 21:20.680
He brooks no bullshit.

21:20.760 --> 21:23.090
But sure.
I'll make the intro.

21:23.180 --> 21:24.550
You'll have to take it
from there.

21:24.640 --> 21:27.090
Then I'll go get that pizza.

21:27.180 --> 21:28.890
Make it a Sicilian?

21:28.970 --> 21:32.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:33.010 --> 21:37.010
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:37.090 --> 21:41.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:43.890 --> 21:46.050
I don't have much experience
with this.

21:46.130 --> 21:47.840
Picking out furniture?

21:47.930 --> 21:49.760
With setting my parents up
in a place.

21:49.840 --> 21:51.300
Getting it furnished.
All of it.

21:51.390 --> 21:54.390
And, yes, I want to use
your eye for style.

21:54.470 --> 21:58.220
You have a great and specific
sense of style yourself.

21:58.300 --> 22:00.720
Thank you. But they don't
necessarily share my...

22:00.800 --> 22:02.760
Ah.

22:02.840 --> 22:05.090
I'm closer in age to them
than you are.

22:05.180 --> 22:07.800
Yes, but you're not
like them at all.

22:07.890 --> 22:09.760
If they were here, all they'd
notice is what things cost.

22:09.840 --> 22:11.590
Argue about it.

22:11.680 --> 22:13.550
Instead of noticing how these
things might make them feel.

22:13.640 --> 22:15.180
How the clean lines and angles

22:15.260 --> 22:17.390
make for a calm,
ideal environment.

22:17.470 --> 22:19.180
Yet you're clear
you want them here.

22:19.260 --> 22:22.180
I do.
But it'll be different.

22:22.260 --> 22:23.890
It is.

22:23.970 --> 22:25.260
It's a good thing.

22:25.340 --> 22:26.590
Family.

22:26.680 --> 22:27.680
For you.

22:27.760 --> 22:29.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:29.390 --> 22:32.640
But that doesn't mean
it'll be easy.

22:32.720 --> 22:34.470
Or should be.

22:34.550 --> 22:37.890
Like when someone... man, woman,
whomever... has a baby.

22:37.970 --> 22:41.430
It's undoubtedly good,
but it's not cost neutral.

22:41.510 --> 22:45.220
Family creates obligation
and stress,

22:45.300 --> 22:49.050
distraction, pain,
vulnerability.

22:49.130 --> 22:50.590
I mean, the hope is that
the connection,

22:50.680 --> 22:53.470
the shared history,
the love matters more.

22:53.550 --> 22:55.970
Some people use it as a brand
new source of motivation.

22:56.050 --> 22:58.430
They do.

22:58.510 --> 23:00.090
Then I guess I do
see it that way.

23:00.180 --> 23:01.680
That's the justification.

23:01.760 --> 23:03.300
We have a new start at a family.

23:03.390 --> 23:05.680
And I really want it to work.

23:05.760 --> 23:07.680
Then I'm sure it will.

23:07.760 --> 23:11.550
And whatever cost will be
small enough to not even matter.

23:11.640 --> 23:14.550
In the grand scheme.

23:14.640 --> 23:16.840
Mr. Beaufort,
come on in.

23:16.930 --> 23:19.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:19.130 --> 23:22.260
They call me "Hard Bob,"
and you know why?

23:22.340 --> 23:24.050
I have an idea.

23:24.130 --> 23:26.090
'Cause I brook no bullshit.

23:26.180 --> 23:27.970
Neither do I.

23:28.050 --> 23:29.550
Now the reason I wanted
to talk to you

23:29.640 --> 23:32.220
is because I have something of
a special favor.

23:32.300 --> 23:35.130
I only took this meeting because
the Secretary asked me to.

23:35.220 --> 23:36.840
But that doesn't mean
I have to do what you ask

23:36.930 --> 23:39.800
or even listen to your ask.

23:39.890 --> 23:41.470
Got it?

23:41.550 --> 23:43.680
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:43.760 --> 23:47.890
[TELEPHONE RINGS]

23:47.970 --> 23:49.130
Sonny.

23:49.220 --> 23:50.510
CHUCK: Hello, Dad.

23:50.590 --> 23:53.390
Is this the daily
"I love you" call?

23:53.470 --> 23:55.390
Son, I have neither time
nor inclination

23:55.470 --> 23:58.130
to dicker around with
protestations of emotion.

23:58.220 --> 24:01.180
SENIOR: If you need my words as
reassurance of affection...

24:01.260 --> 24:02.970
Oh, no, no.
No, sir.

24:03.050 --> 24:05.760
Your feelings are made manifest
with each interaction.

24:05.840 --> 24:07.840
I should hope so.

24:07.930 --> 24:09.800
Now, look.

24:09.890 --> 24:14.800
I have run into a financing snag
with my development.

24:14.890 --> 24:18.970
SENIOR: Banks used to be set up
by gentlemen, for gentlemen.

24:19.050 --> 24:22.300
But a couple of Keatings and
Madoffs behave unscrupulously,

24:22.390 --> 24:26.010
and now the personal touch,
the respect, is gone.

24:26.090 --> 24:30.430
Banks have... have become
businesses without souls.

24:30.510 --> 24:32.180
I'm pretty sure banks
never had souls, Dad.

24:32.260 --> 24:33.640
What's the problem?

24:33.720 --> 24:35.510
They want too much collateral.

24:35.590 --> 24:38.680
Assets that
I've otherwise outlaid.

24:38.760 --> 24:41.890
Now, I know you have some
banking contacts these days.

24:41.970 --> 24:43.680
Highly placed.

24:43.760 --> 24:45.800
SENIOR: If I could find
some favorable terms...

24:45.890 --> 24:48.130
And you want to discuss
this with me here,

24:48.220 --> 24:50.720
while I'm at the epicenter
of New York law?

24:50.800 --> 24:54.220
While I'm in the Attorney
General's very chair.

24:54.300 --> 24:57.180
I'm talking to you as a son,
not the AG.

24:57.260 --> 25:00.640
SENIOR: And you know how
you know that?

25:00.720 --> 25:04.760
Because I would never
tell some random AG

25:04.840 --> 25:06.180
how much I love him.

25:06.260 --> 25:09.010
[LAUGHS]

25:09.090 --> 25:10.180
Okay.

25:10.260 --> 25:11.550
Fine, old man,

25:11.640 --> 25:13.180
CHUCK: I'll try to help.

25:13.260 --> 25:14.430
CHUCK: Know why?

25:14.510 --> 25:16.800
CHUCK: Because I love you, too.

25:16.890 --> 25:18.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:18.300 --> 25:21.090
SENIOR: Oh, for the love o' Christ.

25:21.180 --> 25:25.840
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

25:25.930 --> 25:29.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:29.510 --> 25:32.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:33.050 --> 25:36.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:36.590 --> 25:39.010
So how are we going to
skin this...

25:39.090 --> 25:42.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:42.890 --> 25:45.760
Who we looking to field dress,
Secretary Krakow?

25:45.840 --> 25:47.890
You sold me over,
you sonofabitch.

25:47.970 --> 25:50.970
That's a very untextured
way of thinking, Todd.

25:51.050 --> 25:52.890
Don't do it.

25:55.760 --> 25:58.590
I know this isn't
what you were looking for.

25:58.680 --> 25:59.890
But this is the best...
And only...

25:59.970 --> 26:01.220
Option out there for you

26:01.300 --> 26:03.180
once you ended up
on law enforcement radar.

26:03.260 --> 26:05.680
He's right.

26:05.760 --> 26:07.890
And it won't be all bad.

26:07.970 --> 26:11.430
Oh.

26:14.590 --> 26:18.010
Now have a seat, Mr. Secretary,
we have much to discuss.

26:18.090 --> 26:20.510
Starting with your activities
in the tropics

26:20.590 --> 26:23.300
CHUCK: but perhaps ending
with you a free man,

26:23.390 --> 26:26.680
without any harm to your future
prospects or reputation.

26:26.760 --> 26:29.260
See?
Not all bad.

26:32.930 --> 26:34.390
Okay, counselor.

26:34.470 --> 26:36.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:36.590 --> 26:37.930
Hit me.

26:38.010 --> 26:42.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:43.050 --> 26:44.050
[DOOR CLOSES]

26:44.130 --> 26:45.430
[CHUCKLES]

26:45.510 --> 26:49.260
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:49.340 --> 26:51.510
It'll be a couple of weeks
until the long form contracts

26:51.590 --> 26:52.890
are ready to be signed, but...

26:52.970 --> 26:55.050
I'm eager to proceed.
I don't want paperwork

26:55.130 --> 26:57.510
to stop us from making
certain project deadlines.

26:57.590 --> 27:00.220
Great. If we can start ordering
the materials and equipment...

27:00.300 --> 27:02.130
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

27:02.220 --> 27:03.550
God, I hate interrupting.

27:03.640 --> 27:04.840
But some guy from
the government is here

27:04.930 --> 27:07.260
and kind of demanding
to see you.

27:10.430 --> 27:12.220
Hello, folks.

27:12.300 --> 27:13.890
I'm Robert Beaufort.

27:13.970 --> 27:17.970
I'm from the Bureau of
Industry and Security.

27:18.050 --> 27:21.300
I've become aware of your tech

27:21.390 --> 27:24.340
from my brethren
over in the patent office.

27:24.430 --> 27:26.300
In fact, they stuck a flag in it

27:26.390 --> 27:29.260
and fired it over to me
in the old pneumatic tube.

27:33.050 --> 27:34.720
Being humorous.
We don't use the tubes.

27:34.800 --> 27:36.760
They emailed me.

27:36.840 --> 27:39.590
Anyhow, we're going to need to
hold up any production plans.

27:39.680 --> 27:41.050
DOUGLAS: That's an insane request.

27:41.130 --> 27:44.010
This is intended for private
sector, non military use.

27:44.090 --> 27:45.970
This is not a request.

27:46.050 --> 27:47.760
This is sensitive technology

27:47.840 --> 27:49.970
with national defense
and security implications.

27:50.050 --> 27:52.890
My understanding of the
Bureau's... your department's...

27:52.970 --> 27:54.300
Role is to aid and support

27:54.390 --> 27:55.760
innovation in
the private sector.

27:55.840 --> 27:57.640
It can be, and it is.

27:57.720 --> 27:59.800
But above that
our mandate is security,

27:59.890 --> 28:02.800
especially when it comes to the
export of sensitive technology.

28:02.890 --> 28:05.640
We have, under authority
of the government,

28:05.720 --> 28:07.760
the power to seize
and control said tech

28:07.840 --> 28:09.340
in the name of
our nation's safety.

28:09.430 --> 28:10.800
It's true.

28:10.890 --> 28:15.130
We have determined
that US 18/287,134

28:15.220 --> 28:18.550
is vital to national security
at this time.

28:18.640 --> 28:20.390
You do have the right
to challenge

28:20.470 --> 28:22.180
at an administrative proceeding.

28:22.260 --> 28:24.680
If we do that,
the tech gets public.

28:24.760 --> 28:26.800
BEAUFORT: Exactly.
Which is why we prefer

28:26.890 --> 28:28.260
BEAUFORT: to forgo the hearings

28:28.340 --> 28:29.840
BEAUFORT: and the attendant publicity.

28:29.930 --> 28:31.930
We do in extraordinary cases
like this

28:32.010 --> 28:35.340
offer to cover R&D spending
to date,

28:35.430 --> 28:39.840
plus an 8% premium on investment
for an NDA on the matter.

28:39.930 --> 28:41.760
We're going to need an opinion
of counsel before any...

28:41.840 --> 28:43.300
Of course.

28:43.390 --> 28:45.340
Didn't expect anything
signed today.

28:45.430 --> 28:48.800
I will, however,
leave you with this.

28:48.890 --> 28:52.720
This is an order
outlining which materials

28:52.800 --> 28:55.220
I expect to be turned over
immediately.

28:55.300 --> 28:57.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:57.430 --> 28:59.390
You have my card.

28:59.470 --> 29:00.720
We'll be in touch.

29:00.800 --> 29:03.640
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

29:03.720 --> 29:07.760
Listen, folks, my investment
is entirely contingent

29:07.840 --> 29:10.220
upon you making
this problem disappear.

29:10.300 --> 29:13.010
Instantly.

29:13.090 --> 29:15.180
I've got a meeting.

29:19.840 --> 29:21.390
Shit.

29:21.470 --> 29:23.470
This was Bobby Axelrod.

29:23.550 --> 29:28.430
[LAUGHTER]

29:28.510 --> 29:30.590
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

29:30.680 --> 29:33.720
Holy fuck this one felt good.

29:33.800 --> 29:36.680
You think about
how to entice a man.

29:36.760 --> 29:38.260
What he loves.

29:38.340 --> 29:40.180
Of course, it all starts with
girls and money.

29:40.260 --> 29:42.130
AXE: But it gets more
complicated from there...

29:42.220 --> 29:47.050
Yeah, cars, property, jobs,
access to special doctors,

29:47.130 --> 29:50.220
schools for their kids,
life dreams, goals.

29:50.300 --> 29:52.050
You know, sometimes
it even gets spiritual...

29:52.130 --> 29:54.090
Vatican tours, with the Pope
washing their feet,

29:54.180 --> 29:56.430
meeting the Dalai Lama,
whatever.

29:56.510 --> 29:57.430
And in this case?

29:57.510 --> 29:58.640
Was it Vatican City?

29:58.720 --> 30:00.220
This case?
Oh, no.

30:00.300 --> 30:02.220
This case, no, it turned out
to be girls and money.

30:02.300 --> 30:05.180
[LAUGHTER]

30:05.260 --> 30:06.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:06.840 --> 30:09.180
Hard Bob Beaufort is a film fan.

30:09.260 --> 30:11.930
Turns out,
he really loves the classics.

30:12.010 --> 30:15.050
AXE: Ladies,

30:15.130 --> 30:17.130
this is Hard Bob.

30:17.220 --> 30:19.050
Hello, Hard Bob.

30:19.130 --> 30:20.260
I'm Lisa Ann.

30:20.340 --> 30:22.180
I know.

30:22.260 --> 30:24.640
I know.
And you're...

30:24.720 --> 30:27.550
That's right, Hard Bob, I am.

30:27.640 --> 30:29.840
[UP-TEMPO MUSIC]

30:29.930 --> 30:32.640
Well, this is not the zoo,
Hard Bob.

30:32.720 --> 30:35.930
You can come as close
as you want.

30:36.010 --> 30:40.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:40.720 --> 30:44.470
VIVIAN: Look at this picture.

30:44.550 --> 30:46.090
Really look at it.

30:46.180 --> 30:48.130
Ah.

30:48.220 --> 30:49.640
Mr. Vivian.

30:49.720 --> 30:51.130
Uh, may I call you Shel?

30:51.220 --> 30:53.340
Shelby. Sure.

30:53.430 --> 30:55.720
Mr. Eisen here is a trusted friend.

30:55.800 --> 30:58.390
And when he asked if
I could see you, I said yes.

30:58.470 --> 31:00.130
But I fail to see...

31:00.220 --> 31:03.010
Well, I can see
how special the animal was,

31:03.090 --> 31:05.680
but I can't see how I have
anything to do with this matter.

31:05.760 --> 31:07.760
You can't,
Mr. Rhoades?

31:07.840 --> 31:09.090
Can I call you Charles?

31:09.180 --> 31:11.130
Chuck.

31:11.220 --> 31:14.090
Chuck. Sure.

31:14.180 --> 31:18.090
Well, Eisen here wants me
to settle for 100K.

31:18.180 --> 31:19.760
You did settle for 100K.

31:19.840 --> 31:21.510
I have the papers.
Signed.

31:21.590 --> 31:23.640
And I gave you a check.

31:23.720 --> 31:26.510
Here's that check
right back at you.

31:26.590 --> 31:30.640
And here's another picture
for you to look at, Chuck,

31:30.720 --> 31:33.260
which might tell the story

31:33.340 --> 31:36.180
as to why I am in your office.

31:36.260 --> 31:40.260
I know what this whole thing is.

31:41.720 --> 31:43.550
Cover up.

31:43.640 --> 31:46.050
No such thing.
That's a wildly overblown term.

31:46.130 --> 31:49.640
Look.

31:49.720 --> 31:54.010
The loss of my Charlemagne

31:54.090 --> 31:57.180
was worth more than
the 100,000 and a new puppy.

31:57.260 --> 32:00.300
Mm.

32:00.390 --> 32:03.260
How much more?

32:03.340 --> 32:06.800
I get 250,000 dollars,
or I go public,

32:06.890 --> 32:09.430
way public, with this
whole damn conspiracy.

32:09.510 --> 32:13.590
There is no conspiracy...
Shelby.

32:13.680 --> 32:15.840
But I see how pained you are.

32:15.930 --> 32:18.010
And I'm moved by it.

32:18.090 --> 32:20.720
Mr. Eisen here
will get with Mr. Brogan

32:20.800 --> 32:23.680
and produce the amount required.

32:23.760 --> 32:28.090
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

32:28.180 --> 32:32.550
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

32:32.640 --> 32:35.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:35.680 --> 32:37.470
Just got off the phone
with the lawyer.

32:37.550 --> 32:39.930
She said what we're facing is
similar to eminent domain.

32:40.010 --> 32:41.340
They can do it,
we can push back.

32:41.430 --> 32:42.840
- Can we win?
- HAMMON: She says maybe.

32:42.930 --> 32:45.840
How long will it take?

32:45.930 --> 32:48.590
Two and a half, three years.

32:52.340 --> 32:55.220
I spun like Katarina Witt
in Sarajevo

32:55.300 --> 32:57.680
but there's nothing new out
there ready to come on board.

32:57.760 --> 33:00.590
LAUREN: I made the rounds with
our current investors, too.

33:00.680 --> 33:03.340
We may lose some.

33:03.430 --> 33:05.130
I need to sit with
the Firefighters.

33:05.220 --> 33:06.890
Get me a meeting
with Ken Shaddock.

33:06.970 --> 33:09.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.050 --> 33:13.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:13.180 --> 33:16.640
[KEYS CLACKING]

33:16.720 --> 33:19.840
Your ex-protégé is a hell of
a businessperson.

33:19.930 --> 33:22.340
Sniffing out the initial trap
was smart.

33:22.430 --> 33:24.130
They are indeed.

33:24.220 --> 33:26.090
That's what's gonna
make it so rewarding

33:26.180 --> 33:27.590
when they take the smart
business decision

33:27.680 --> 33:29.130
to crush their father.

33:29.220 --> 33:32.050
Because what they won't know,
until it's too late,

33:32.130 --> 33:35.300
is how hollow
it will make them feel.

33:38.220 --> 33:41.130
Uh, remind me to never
stab you in the back.

33:41.220 --> 33:42.390
Consider yourself reminded.

33:42.470 --> 33:44.130
Mm-hmm.

33:44.220 --> 33:45.930
What's that you're devouring

33:46.010 --> 33:47.470
like a gluten-free croissant
over there?

33:47.550 --> 33:49.010
Oh, kiss my ass.

33:49.090 --> 33:51.090
You know I don't fuck with
gluten-free.

33:51.180 --> 33:52.340
And this is my next thing.

33:52.430 --> 33:53.470
Saler's department stores.

33:53.550 --> 33:55.130
Huh.

33:55.220 --> 33:56.510
That chain's like
a wheezing elephant

33:56.590 --> 33:57.970
ready to stumble to its knees.

33:58.050 --> 33:59.720
Uh, until I get a hold of it

33:59.800 --> 34:02.510
and hit it in the ass with
a giant shot of B-12.

34:02.590 --> 34:04.050
You're gonna restore it
to its former glory?

34:04.130 --> 34:05.390
Oh, you're fucking right I am.

34:05.470 --> 34:07.300
There's a lot of debt
against it, babe.

34:07.390 --> 34:09.760
It's not gonna be easy.
Well, I don't do easy.

34:09.840 --> 34:11.179
If I wanted that
I'd move to Florida

34:11.260 --> 34:12.550
and work on my tan with Bruno.

34:12.639 --> 34:15.050
[CHUCKLES]
Yeah.

34:15.130 --> 34:18.590
It's good that he seemed happy
with what I laid out.

34:18.679 --> 34:20.179
Mm.

34:20.260 --> 34:22.760
No?

34:22.840 --> 34:25.800
That is some sweet deal
I'm giving him.

34:25.889 --> 34:28.300
Are you gonna speak or just
sit there silently doubting?

34:28.389 --> 34:31.639
Um...

34:31.719 --> 34:33.679
Bruno knows
you get what you want.

34:33.760 --> 34:35.010
So he's made peace with that.

34:35.090 --> 34:38.010
But he wants to live in Florida.

34:38.090 --> 34:41.260
What kind of life would it be?

34:41.340 --> 34:43.760
Playing canasta with
a bunch of other retirees.

34:43.840 --> 34:45.510
Shuffleboard.

34:45.590 --> 34:47.800
Dragging down to the drugstore
to get his prescriptions?

34:47.889 --> 34:49.090
I don't want that
kind of life for him.

34:49.179 --> 34:51.179
Nothing to fight for.

34:51.260 --> 34:54.719
Nothing to make him feel like
he's still in it.

34:54.800 --> 34:56.260
It's giving up.
Dying.

34:56.340 --> 34:58.680
For you. For you,
it would be giving up.

34:58.760 --> 35:01.510
But maybe for him,
after a lifetime

35:01.590 --> 35:04.220
in front of a hot oven,
it would finally be living.

35:08.430 --> 35:10.340
You put your faith in me.

35:10.430 --> 35:12.010
There's something
sacred in that.

35:12.090 --> 35:14.050
And I'm not the sort
to use that word.

35:14.130 --> 35:15.640
No, no, it is a sacred trust.

35:15.720 --> 35:17.430
There is no other word.

35:17.510 --> 35:19.260
You made me believe
you understood that.

35:19.340 --> 35:21.260
And that you wouldn't
let these firefighters down.

35:21.340 --> 35:24.260
I won't. Even as I wage
this other battle.

35:24.340 --> 35:28.680
You know, before the department
I was in the service,

35:28.760 --> 35:31.390
so I'm a bit of an expert
on two-front wars.

35:31.470 --> 35:35.510
What happens,
no matter how well trained

35:35.590 --> 35:37.340
and capable the army is,

35:37.430 --> 35:38.640
more people die.

35:38.720 --> 35:40.840
I will personally
be down in the muck...

35:40.930 --> 35:43.470
Yeah, see, why is that
a good thing?

35:43.550 --> 35:46.970
In a firefight,
an infantryman's job

35:47.050 --> 35:49.430
is to zero in on his target
and shoot.

35:49.510 --> 35:51.220
To the exclusion of all else.

35:51.300 --> 35:53.930
But he can't see anything else
besides that target

35:54.010 --> 35:55.720
through the aperture
of his rifle sights.

35:55.800 --> 35:57.430
It's a very small picture.

35:57.510 --> 36:00.590
That's why a leader,
as much as he wants to fire,

36:00.680 --> 36:02.590
needs to keep his weapon
at full port arms

36:02.680 --> 36:04.840
and scan the entire battlefield.

36:04.930 --> 36:06.930
To see it all.

36:07.010 --> 36:08.890
SHADDOCK: Let's measure it.

36:08.970 --> 36:10.590
For a normal,
disciplined person,

36:10.680 --> 36:14.430
this kind of engagement
would cost 50 percent.

36:14.510 --> 36:16.300
So even for you,

36:16.390 --> 36:18.890
will it cost you 20,

36:18.970 --> 36:22.340
or 10, even 3 percent?

36:22.430 --> 36:24.840
Let's say you're right,
for the sake of argument.

36:24.930 --> 36:26.640
At 97 percent focused,

36:26.720 --> 36:29.220
I am certain you will not see
any change in results.

36:29.300 --> 36:31.720
But to guarantee that,
let's do this.

36:31.800 --> 36:33.550
Stay with me as long
as we're positive.

36:33.640 --> 36:36.340
TAYLOR: But the moment I slip
into negative territory,

36:36.430 --> 36:37.930
I return your money that day.

36:38.010 --> 36:40.090
It's virtually risk proof
for you.

36:40.180 --> 36:42.800
No deal, Mason.

36:42.890 --> 36:44.760
You dump the other company
or we go.

36:44.840 --> 36:47.890
I'm sorry this didn't work out.

36:47.970 --> 36:50.260
I know we would've done
great work together.

36:50.340 --> 36:52.340
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

36:52.430 --> 36:54.390
Okay.

36:54.470 --> 36:57.010
[DOOR OPENS]

36:57.090 --> 37:00.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:00.510 --> 37:03.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:03.720 --> 37:06.050
HAMMON: So?

37:06.130 --> 37:08.430
He put me to a decision
and I had to let him go.

37:08.510 --> 37:09.970
Shit.

37:10.050 --> 37:11.800
TAYLOR: How went it with Dana?

37:11.890 --> 37:13.550
He's out, too.

37:13.640 --> 37:17.010
He says sorry and hopes
to see us down the road.

37:17.090 --> 37:19.760
And I talked to the lawyer,
the bank and accounting.

37:19.840 --> 37:22.300
You're gonna have to drive
this yourself, carry the risk.

37:22.390 --> 37:24.300
Bank's gonna want you to
put up the money yourself.

37:24.390 --> 37:25.720
Your bonus from last year.

37:25.800 --> 37:29.130
Or we get the broker
to do a securities loan.

37:29.220 --> 37:30.800
Fine.
But no margin.

37:30.890 --> 37:32.720
Yeah.
I can get that done.

37:32.800 --> 37:34.800
I'm not sure you should.

37:34.890 --> 37:36.640
It's a big fucking commitment.

37:36.720 --> 37:38.550
A big commitment
has already been made.

37:38.640 --> 37:40.720
And it holds. It has to.
To my father.

37:40.800 --> 37:42.680
You have another.

37:42.760 --> 37:45.180
To Taylor Mason Capital itself.

37:45.260 --> 37:47.970
You have to make both work.

37:48.050 --> 37:50.390
Or none of it will.

37:50.470 --> 37:53.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:53.130 --> 37:55.300
I just got word.

37:55.390 --> 37:57.430
The Firefighters Fund is gon-zo.

37:57.510 --> 37:59.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:59.640 --> 38:01.640
That's check.

38:01.720 --> 38:03.760
You ready to go topple the king?

38:03.840 --> 38:06.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:06.590 --> 38:08.300
[CELLPHONE VIBRATING]

38:08.390 --> 38:09.930
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

38:10.010 --> 38:11.010
Hello?

38:11.090 --> 38:12.590
I need to see you.

38:12.680 --> 38:14.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:14.680 --> 38:16.930
Now.

38:17.010 --> 38:19.180
Promise me this conversation
stays private.

38:19.260 --> 38:21.510
That's the understanding
we've had the whole time.

38:21.590 --> 38:23.010
I just want to restate it.

38:23.090 --> 38:24.800
Because I need to
tell you something,

38:24.890 --> 38:27.800
and it's...
It's a big risk for me.

38:27.890 --> 38:30.550
You have my word.

38:30.640 --> 38:33.800
Axe knows you lost
the Firefighters.

38:33.890 --> 38:36.470
He said they were
the air support

38:36.550 --> 38:39.010
protecting the rest
of your ventures.

38:39.090 --> 38:41.510
He said you chose your father
over your business.

38:45.090 --> 38:47.300
[CHUCKLES]
I admire that.

38:47.390 --> 38:50.180
He may not, but I do.

38:50.260 --> 38:53.390
That you can be one of the
people that finds the balance.

38:53.470 --> 38:57.930
Who can be happy at enough.

38:58.010 --> 39:00.550
He could never do that.

39:00.640 --> 39:02.590
But you didn't let the fact

39:02.680 --> 39:05.390
that your father exploited
your need for his approval

39:05.470 --> 39:07.130
stop you from choosing family.

39:07.220 --> 39:10.390
That's truly impressive.

39:12.010 --> 39:14.470
But Axe is coming for you now,

39:14.550 --> 39:16.430
and nothing's going to stop him.

39:16.510 --> 39:18.390
So you came to warn me.

39:21.390 --> 39:24.550
He's so far gone...
with negativity.

39:24.640 --> 39:25.890
Annihilation.

39:25.970 --> 39:28.680
Annihilating you, in particular.

39:28.760 --> 39:32.050
I've never seen such
single-mindedness.

39:32.130 --> 39:34.640
It's toxic.

39:34.720 --> 39:36.680
Corrosive.

39:36.760 --> 39:40.260
I went to work for
a financial genius,

39:40.340 --> 39:42.130
not Shiva the Destroyer.

39:42.220 --> 39:44.390
It gets hard to be around.

39:44.470 --> 39:47.840
How can you even stand
working there anymore?

39:47.930 --> 39:51.590
I'm not sure I can.

39:51.680 --> 39:55.680
I'm not sure I can be a part of
what he's planning.

39:55.760 --> 39:57.340
I'm thinking about quitting.

39:57.430 --> 39:59.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:59.840 --> 40:01.510
Nope. Fuck.

40:01.590 --> 40:03.130
You're not here to warn me.

40:03.220 --> 40:05.590
"I'm thinking about quitting."
That's one too many.

40:05.680 --> 40:07.340
I've trained myself to recognize

40:07.430 --> 40:08.930
when someone overplays
their hand,

40:09.010 --> 40:10.260
and you did, just now.

40:10.340 --> 40:14.510
But you've built
the perfect box.

40:14.590 --> 40:17.680
No escape without
catastrophic loss.

40:17.760 --> 40:20.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:20.970 --> 40:24.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:24.550 --> 40:27.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.050 --> 40:30.680
That furniture will look good
in this place.

40:30.760 --> 40:34.760
I hope your parents
are happy here.

40:34.840 --> 40:38.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:39.010 --> 40:42.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:43.010 --> 40:47.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:47.180 --> 40:51.260
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:51.340 --> 40:55.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:55.590 --> 40:57.760
Ken Shaddock, please.

40:57.840 --> 41:02.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:02.130 --> 41:03.890
Positive news, Dad.

41:03.970 --> 41:06.760
My prostate is gonna shrink
back to its former size?

41:06.840 --> 41:09.590
Not that, but it may make you
smile just as much.

41:09.680 --> 41:12.590
Qatar State Bank is going to be
taken off the restricted list

41:12.680 --> 41:14.930
and it's ready to give you
a sweetheart of a loan.

41:15.010 --> 41:18.640
Well, you're right,
that does bring a grin.

41:18.720 --> 41:20.640
SENIOR: Are you sure about this?

41:20.720 --> 41:22.930
CHUCK: Got it straight from
the Secretary Of The Treasury.

41:23.010 --> 41:25.590
[CLEARS THROAT]

41:25.680 --> 41:29.050
You know Jewish people have 613 rules...
mitzvot...

41:29.130 --> 41:30.930
For determining
what's kosher in life?

41:31.010 --> 41:33.300
"Hey, what don't you know?"
"Innit?"

41:33.390 --> 41:34.890
And in this country we've got

41:34.970 --> 41:36.510
about a million
banking regulations...

41:36.590 --> 41:38.680
And this has got to violate
a bunch of them.

41:38.760 --> 41:40.300
Oh, this shit is definitely
not kashrut.

41:40.390 --> 41:41.220
Oh hoh.
You're not the only one

41:41.300 --> 41:43.010
who lives in the big city.

41:43.090 --> 41:45.930
Now, unless the bank
came off the list legitimately,

41:46.010 --> 41:47.430
in which case... In which case

41:47.510 --> 41:49.260
we could take a look
at why it came off the list.

41:49.340 --> 41:51.340
How, exactly? Why now?
Who was behind it?

41:51.430 --> 41:52.970
You want to start
getting those answers?

41:53.050 --> 41:54.130
Love to.
Great.

41:54.220 --> 41:56.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:58.680 --> 42:00.890
Dad, I have something for you.

42:07.720 --> 42:09.390
What the fuck is this?

42:09.470 --> 42:12.010
A check for
1.3 million dollars.

42:12.090 --> 42:15.470
You caved.

42:15.550 --> 42:17.970
You folded and took the deal?

42:20.260 --> 42:22.470
Government's gonna
mothball my project.

42:22.550 --> 42:25.300
Or worse, deploy it
as they see fit.

42:25.390 --> 42:28.010
I assessed all the options
and it was the only one left.

42:28.090 --> 42:29.930
It was not the only one.

42:30.010 --> 42:32.720
It was the only one that allowed
me to get the Firefighters back,

42:32.800 --> 42:34.180
which will save this place,

42:34.260 --> 42:36.090
because without it,
there is nothing.

42:36.180 --> 42:39.840
There's my life's work,

42:39.930 --> 42:42.390
my tech,

42:42.470 --> 42:44.390
my fucking dream.

42:45.720 --> 42:50.010
Which to you is nothing
in the face of

42:50.090 --> 42:52.640
recoupment of your investment

42:52.720 --> 42:57.050
plus 8 fucking percent.

42:57.130 --> 42:58.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:58.550 --> 43:00.220
I'm sorry it worked out
this way.

43:00.300 --> 43:03.430
It's unfortunate but my enemies
seemed to have found a way

43:03.510 --> 43:06.050
to aim the government at us
like a nuclear weapon.

43:06.130 --> 43:08.180
How did they know where to aim?

43:08.260 --> 43:09.840
How did they know
to hurt this venture?

43:09.930 --> 43:12.510
I did it.

43:12.590 --> 43:15.010
I told Wendy about your dad.

43:15.090 --> 43:17.090
Not... Not really.
She seemed to know.

43:17.180 --> 43:19.720
I just said
the word 'startup.'

43:19.800 --> 43:22.760
How, exactly, did you and
Wendy Rhoades end up talking?

43:22.840 --> 43:24.130
S-She just...

43:24.220 --> 43:25.680
She was supposed to
meet a friend,

43:25.760 --> 43:27.970
and the friend didn't show.

43:28.050 --> 43:30.640
Oh, Taylor, I got played.

43:30.720 --> 43:32.760
No, Mafee, I got played.

43:32.840 --> 43:34.390
You were mere confirmation.

43:34.470 --> 43:36.180
I, too, spoke with her.

43:36.260 --> 43:37.840
At first,
I thought it was benign.

43:37.930 --> 43:39.840
Then I thought
I could use the forum,

43:39.930 --> 43:42.300
gain from it,
but instead I was infected.

43:42.390 --> 43:44.720
DOUGLAS: The fact that
you have enemies like this,

43:44.800 --> 43:46.840
the fact that
you were once aligned

43:46.930 --> 43:49.260
with such despicable people,

43:49.340 --> 43:52.720
maybe give that some thought
while I'm gone.

43:52.800 --> 43:55.340
So you're leaving?
We could try ano...

43:55.430 --> 43:57.050
You're damn skippy I'm leaving.

43:57.130 --> 44:01.090
What's possibly going to
keep me here now?

44:01.180 --> 44:03.010
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:03.090 --> 44:04.760
Yeah.

44:04.840 --> 44:06.930
This is one time I'm sorry
my thesis proves out.

44:07.010 --> 44:08.510
Thesis?

44:08.590 --> 44:10.680
You taught me,
don't just have an idea.

44:10.760 --> 44:13.720
Build the model that proves it.

44:13.800 --> 44:17.090
Sara, call Shaddock
with the Firefighters.

44:17.180 --> 44:19.680
Tell him I did what I said
and we're back in business.

44:21.470 --> 44:23.430
Wait, this is all a test?

44:23.510 --> 44:25.890
Not a test.
A confirmation.

44:25.970 --> 44:28.220
I needed to remind myself
who you really are.

44:28.300 --> 44:29.800
Wendy said it.

44:29.890 --> 44:31.550
I didn't want her to be right,
but she was.

44:31.640 --> 44:33.720
I didn't chose the Firefighters
over you, Dad.

44:33.800 --> 44:35.930
I chose what you wanted
over what I needed.

44:36.010 --> 44:39.430
Don't you need me?

44:39.510 --> 44:41.640
Yes, and I always have.

44:41.720 --> 44:43.800
But the version of you
I really need...

44:43.890 --> 44:46.010
The one who's a father first...
He doesn't exist.

44:46.090 --> 44:48.430
'Cause all he cares about
is his own advancement.

44:48.510 --> 44:52.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:52.260 --> 44:55.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:55.680 --> 44:57.180
I'm leaving.

44:57.260 --> 44:59.720
And I'm taking my
fin technology with me.

44:59.800 --> 45:02.220
No, you're not.
I owned it.

45:02.300 --> 45:03.970
And I sold it to the government.

45:04.050 --> 45:07.430
You people.

45:07.510 --> 45:09.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:09.640 --> 45:12.970
All you care about
is fucking money.

45:13.050 --> 45:16.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:16.260 --> 45:19.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:19.720 --> 45:23.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:23.260 --> 45:25.430
You know what, kid?

45:25.510 --> 45:27.180
You are just like me.

45:27.260 --> 45:28.470
Only colder.

45:28.550 --> 45:30.050
Yeah.

45:30.130 --> 45:32.550
So maybe I'll actually win.

45:32.640 --> 45:36.430
Maybe, but I'll say this.

45:36.510 --> 45:39.970
It won't feel like it.

45:40.050 --> 45:45.010
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

45:45.090 --> 45:48.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:48.470 --> 45:52.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:52.130 --> 45:55.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:59.970 --> 46:02.510
Sir, you're gonna need
to come with us.

46:02.590 --> 46:04.550
Why?
What the fuck?!

46:04.640 --> 46:06.220
- Come on.
- Don't make us cuff you.

46:06.300 --> 46:08.050
Hey!

46:09.340 --> 46:11.840
[DOOR CLOSES]

46:11.930 --> 46:13.300
Rhoades.

46:13.390 --> 46:15.260
I'm not easily scared.

46:15.340 --> 46:17.930
Especially because you have
no cause of action to arrest me.

46:18.010 --> 46:19.510
Oh, no, no, no, no.

46:19.590 --> 46:21.260
You're not under arrest.

46:21.340 --> 46:24.720
No, in the old days
they called this a 'rousting.'

46:24.800 --> 46:26.550
Now, that's
old-fashioned policing,

46:26.640 --> 46:28.260
designed to send a message.

46:28.340 --> 46:29.640
And where can it go?

46:29.720 --> 46:32.550
Well, you can be brought in.

46:32.640 --> 46:34.760
Put in holding.
You ever visit the Tombs?

46:34.840 --> 46:38.640
It makes for a very edifying
24 to 48 hours.

46:38.720 --> 46:41.840
Or you might be found to be
'resisting, ' on the street,

46:41.930 --> 46:45.390
and then the boys get
a little baton practice.

46:45.470 --> 46:49.050
And these men are
my personal force.

46:49.130 --> 46:51.760
There's nothing that
they won't do for me.

46:51.840 --> 46:53.680
But I don't want to talk about
any of that.

46:53.760 --> 46:56.720
No.
I want to talk about dogs.

46:56.800 --> 46:58.970
And the people who own 'em.

46:59.050 --> 47:01.430
I love a good dog.

47:01.510 --> 47:03.180
I, myself,
have had one for years.

47:03.260 --> 47:06.550
But I don't fool myself,
as so many do.

47:06.640 --> 47:08.300
Fool yourself?
Mm.

47:08.390 --> 47:11.390
About which way the loyalties
really run.

47:11.470 --> 47:15.640
Do you know what happens when
a solo pet owner dies alone?

47:15.720 --> 47:17.970
Nope.

47:18.050 --> 47:20.470
Oh, you don't want to admit
to yourself that you know.

47:20.550 --> 47:22.510
But you do.

47:22.590 --> 47:25.890
At some point, the pet decides
that its own survival

47:25.970 --> 47:28.680
matters more than
its fondness for its owner.

47:28.760 --> 47:31.430
And what do they do?

47:31.510 --> 47:35.010
Well, most often, they go for
the nose or cheek flesh first.

47:35.090 --> 47:37.590
Now, is that because
their love is so great,

47:37.680 --> 47:40.090
they want to be one with
their former best friend?

47:40.180 --> 47:42.130
I don't choose to think so.

47:42.220 --> 47:45.970
No, I just bet those are
the most delicious morsels.

47:46.050 --> 47:48.180
And I don't blame 'em at all.

47:48.260 --> 47:51.510
Because when their very lives
are at stake,

47:51.590 --> 47:52.930
how can they stand on ceremony?

47:53.010 --> 47:57.340
After all, their owner
is already dead.

47:57.430 --> 48:00.220
But I'm not in desperate straits
as the dog in your story is.

48:00.300 --> 48:02.640
Oh, but you are.

48:02.720 --> 48:06.550
You don't really think
Eisen put you in front of me

48:06.640 --> 48:08.800
without us knowing
what would happen, do you?

48:08.890 --> 48:11.470
He brought you in so that,
in front of a witness,

48:11.550 --> 48:12.800
you would try to extort

48:12.890 --> 48:15.130
the sitting
New York Attorney General.

48:15.220 --> 48:17.760
With threats to expose him
if he didn't pay you off.

48:17.840 --> 48:20.220
That's an open and shut case.

48:20.300 --> 48:22.890
Your own lawyer would
force you to take a plea

48:22.970 --> 48:24.720
the first day you engaged him.

48:24.800 --> 48:27.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:27.220 --> 48:30.340
But, because, as I said,
I'm a dog guy,

48:30.430 --> 48:32.760
I understand why
you felt you had to.

48:32.840 --> 48:35.220
Still the dog is dead.

48:35.300 --> 48:39.890
And you are sitting here
starving.

48:39.970 --> 48:41.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:41.890 --> 48:43.760
I see.

48:43.840 --> 48:46.180
But, and here's the day
brightener for you.

48:46.260 --> 48:49.220
I have no need to bring this
into open court.

48:49.300 --> 48:54.260
What I propose to do instead is

48:54.340 --> 48:58.130
give you this.

49:00.890 --> 49:02.390
Ah.

49:02.470 --> 49:04.550
That's a purebred
Belgian Malinois puppy.

49:04.640 --> 49:06.010
With papers.

49:06.090 --> 49:07.300
And it's yours.

49:07.390 --> 49:10.430
Along with
the 100,000 already paid.

49:10.510 --> 49:14.050
And you sign this.

49:17.890 --> 49:19.390
Which says I drop my complaint.

49:19.470 --> 49:21.470
It sure does.

49:21.550 --> 49:25.050
Now and forever.

49:31.390 --> 49:35.300
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

49:35.390 --> 49:36.340
Hi, Mafee!

49:36.430 --> 49:37.590
Not now, Ben.

49:37.680 --> 49:39.130
You.

49:39.220 --> 49:41.680
Do you have any fucking idea
what you've done?

49:41.760 --> 49:44.090
I used to think you were this
idealized version of a person

49:44.180 --> 49:45.640
with all the answers
and the ability to make

49:45.720 --> 49:47.220
each of us the best
of who we could be.

49:47.300 --> 49:49.300
I trusted you.
We all did.

49:49.390 --> 49:51.930
Because you charmed,
manipulated, worked us to.

49:52.010 --> 49:54.050
All with that bullshit
Buddha smile.

49:54.130 --> 49:56.430
And now I know that what
was behind that smile

49:56.510 --> 49:58.010
wasn't some serene
and wise teacher.

49:58.090 --> 50:00.470
Hey!
It hid a sick, vicious phony.

50:00.550 --> 50:02.840
Now I know that's what you
really are... a goddamned monster.

50:02.930 --> 50:05.090
Hey!
Traitorous motherfucker.

50:05.180 --> 50:07.010
Yeah, leave her alone,
you fucking goon!

50:07.090 --> 50:08.680
You tried to sabotage this firm!

50:08.760 --> 50:10.470
Fuck you, Bill!
You don't talk to a man

50:10.550 --> 50:11.800
like Dollar Bill Stearn
like that.

50:11.890 --> 50:13.010
- Fuck you, too!
- Guys. Mafee...

50:13.090 --> 50:14.640
I am gonna kick your ass!

50:14.720 --> 50:15.930
Bring it, asshole!

50:16.010 --> 50:17.180
Let it happen.
We both want it.

50:17.260 --> 50:18.550
No fighting where
Mr. Axelrod is liable.

50:18.640 --> 50:19.840
I'll sign whatever!
That's two of us!

50:19.930 --> 50:21.180
Get him outta here!

50:21.260 --> 50:22.930
Let's do it in the ring then,
fucknut!

50:23.010 --> 50:25.470
Any time, any place,
motherfucker!

50:25.550 --> 50:28.930
Rumble in the Jungle!
Thrilla in Manila! Zaire!

50:29.010 --> 50:30.340
You're a garbage person, Wendy.

50:30.430 --> 50:32.510
That's what you are.
It's what you all are!

50:32.590 --> 50:34.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:34.970 --> 50:36.930
Fuck you.

50:37.010 --> 50:39.260
I guess we hit the target.

50:39.340 --> 50:44.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:44.180 --> 50:49.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:51.590 --> 50:54.130
It's done.

50:54.220 --> 50:56.550
Done means signed,
sealed, delivered.

50:56.640 --> 50:58.300
Is that what you're telling me?
I am.

50:58.390 --> 51:00.890
He acknowledges that
his dog was a repeated menace

51:00.970 --> 51:02.930
and you acted in self-defense.

51:03.010 --> 51:04.590
He releases you
from responsibility

51:04.680 --> 51:06.930
and will not tell
or sell the story.

51:07.010 --> 51:08.970
Welp. Now we know,
definitively.

51:09.050 --> 51:10.300
You really are a power broker.

51:10.390 --> 51:13.010
And, uh, I'm gonna
say it directly,

51:13.090 --> 51:15.720
so it's between us
and acknowledged.

51:15.800 --> 51:19.800
Down the 'pike, I will
ask something of you.

51:19.890 --> 51:22.180
Something hard.

51:22.260 --> 51:24.890
Something that will be
very costly for you to do.

51:24.970 --> 51:28.760
And you will deliver it for me.

51:28.840 --> 51:30.800
I will.

51:30.890 --> 51:33.680
You've shown me, by example,
what might happen if I don't.

51:36.840 --> 51:39.130
Can I have it back?

51:41.720 --> 51:44.430
[CLEARS THROAT]

51:44.510 --> 51:47.720
That thing goes off again,

51:47.800 --> 51:50.390
lose my number.

